english:
  title: A Letter to the Venerable Minseon
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Confucian scholars mock me, saying, 'You speak well of Buddhist doctrine, just like a monk. You cast no nets, fish with no lines, deplore the taking of life—this is even more like a monk. Why not shave your crown and don the dark robes?' The Buddhists, in turn, mock me, saying, 'You speak well of Buddhist doctrine, just as we do. You cast no nets, fish with no lines, and deplore the taking of life—this is even more like us. Yet you keep many concubines, raise sons and grandsons, love your wine and spirits, and eat chicken and pork indiscriminately. How can your conduct be so contradictory?'

    Alas! With this limited body of mine, attacked from both sides by Confucians and Buddhists alike, how difficult it is to be human! Yet what brings me joy is the Way itself. I cherish the Way—what matter if Confucians and Buddhists alike attack me with their competing claims?

    But hear me: I do not revile or praise others. When Confucian scholars come, I must tell them of the Way of Poetry, History, Benevolence, and Righteousness. If they listen, I rejoice. When Buddhist monks come, I likewise tell them of the Way of Poetry, History, Benevolence, and Righteousness. Some listen, some do not. If they listen, I rejoice; if they do not, I harbor no resentment.

    Venerable Minseon of the Huayan school, having mistakenly heard that I could write, came seeking me through the dense grass. One day, entering my chamber and hearing the sound of me reciting, his countenance seemed to brighten, as if awakening to some deeper understanding. Then I repeated to him what I have always told both Confucians and Buddhists. If Minseon expands his learning to roam freely in the gardens of the Two Sage-Emperors and Three Kings, if his inquiry deepens to plumb the wellsprings of all principles and the Four Sprouts of virtue, then perhaps he will understand that what I teach does not contradict the Way—that Confucians may see it as Confucianism, and Buddhists as Buddhism.

    Moreover, the sages of old never abandoned human relations nor destroyed the bonds of kinship to appear transcendent. Nor did they kill carelessly or demean the lives of creatures to seem compassionate. In the Five Relations, husband and wife hold their rightful place. The lamb-calf and firewood are not broken; Confucius cast no nets for fish. Thus we see the hearts of the sages. Is it not better to speak of the Way that awakens their hearts, rather than invoke the doctrine of pure emptiness and extinction?

    Therefore, that I am mocked by others stems from my teaching of Poetry, History, Benevolence, and Righteousness—yet my inner joy remains undisturbed. Their mockery and slander are like the fleeting songs of beautiful birds or blossoms fair—they fade without a trace.

    Since Minseon has come to know me well and asks for my words as a gift, and since he already understands what I have always taught others, I share with him again the teachings of Poetry, History, Benevolence, and Righteousness. This accords with what our Master Confucius said: 'Do you think I hide anything? I hide nothing from you.'

    If Minseon carries this forth and asks the noble officials for poems, know that this was not my intention.
  footnotes:
    - The Two Sage-Emperors (二帝) refer to Yao and Shun; the Three Kings (三王) are typically Yu, Tang, and King Wen in Confucian tradition.
    - The Four Sprouts (四端) refer to the four incipient feelings of humanity, righteousness, propriety, and wisdom—key concepts in Mencius's philosophy.
    - The lamb-calf (羔) and firewood (柴) refer to sacrificial offerings used carefully to preserve nature, contrasting with careless slaughter.
    - The phrase 'with what our Master Confucius said' references the Analects 15.3, expressing the complete openness and transparency of a sage's teaching.
